    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-12T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-12T20:00:00-05:00" n="376"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d376">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.20294/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-12T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 12, 1918—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>177. For <persName corresp="#p_HCEM1">House</persName>. The Department is in
                    receipt of a telegram dated the 2nd instant from the Embassy at Tokyo reading as
                    follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Department’s November 30, 6 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d376fn2">Not
                                printed.</note> regarding German propaganda. Reference Embassy’s
                            quarterly report number 3.<note n="2" xml:id="d376fn3">Not
                                printed.</note> Since the collapse of the Central Powers, all traces
                            pro-German sentiment have at least temporarily disappeared, showing that
                            its former strength was at the same time its weakness. That is to say,
                            this propaganda was largely the work of militarists and German educated
                            university professors, whose prestige depended upon preserving
                            institutions of a German pattern and therefore it became thoroughly
                            discredited as soon as it could no longer be demonstrated that Germany
                            was worthy of emulation or expedient to cultivate on account of her
                            strength. In this connection it is significant that none of the Peace
                            Conference delegates on the part of Japan are classed as belonging to
                            the German school. At the present moment I can trace no influences here
                            which would indicate German origin. <persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                                >Morris</persName>.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
